The Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Homecoming and permanent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the virus's life cycle.
Without the HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, no mature infection virus particles would arise.
When we turn off HIV protease, we also turn off the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the scientific newspaper Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of connections in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
A little weaker, but reliable
The effects of this series of substances against HIV protease have been tested in the reagent glass, including their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metalocarborans on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other characteristics, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical developments, makes the metalcarborans interesting links for further research on the development of effective medicines against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the laboratory for structural biology of the Institute for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute for Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
