They learned these lessons so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change course this summer through the low birth rate and the ageing population, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their answer was direct and final: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
For a second child there is nothing left, said Wang, 31, a staff leader with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously thick, reconciled single children, who are lovingly called "small emperors," a population crisis in the country is emerging.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UNO-
The number of population groups from 60 years of age and older is expected to rise from 16.7% of the population by 2050 to 31.1% in an explosive way, much above the global average of about 20%.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with an educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-old and older people accounted for almost 22% of the reported inhabitants of Shanghai, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, Head of the Shanghai City and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of the productive age must have babies to "help reduce the ratio of the ageing population and alleviate the labour shortage of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
In the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy should probably be the most controversial available, which has been introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Married couples who are in breach of this policy must expect enormous fines -- up to their triple annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese government representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical demands on natural resources could be avoided, against which human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, creating an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude to one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many hard slogans was reduced.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that government representatives have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with a single partner.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city administration has sent out urban staff and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and push information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not exactly encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Decommissioning reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outer areas of Shanghai said that a recovery in the applications of couples who want a second child after the launch of the campaign can be seen, the urban districts do not report any change.
For the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are still received per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city expected for 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai municipality of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want to have children anymore.
They want to give their first best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this was also legally allowed.
But they have, like many Chinese, only a small health and life insurance of the government.
Without a social network, they say this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West falsely judge the one-child policy as a human rights issue, Yang said, a construction engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yeah, we're being robbed of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples indicate psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of staff, said she only wants a child because she was also a single child. "We were the center of the family and used to take care of everyone.
We are not used to taking care of others and do not really want to. "
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who belongs to a translation company, said it unblatantly.
For middle-aged parents with a double career through which the birth rate is falling, he said, it's about being successful and you have to be selfish for that.
The age group of today's 20-39-year-old grew up to see their parents fight during the early days of Chinese capitalist experiment and they do not want a life like this for themselves, he said.
Also a single child, he said, makes huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there is the space question -- "You have to change your apartment" -- and life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you already have a CV for the best preschool."
Most of his friends are ready to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group draft emission reduction plan
The UN-funded climate conference - which has so far been characterised by wild potions and mutual accusations - has again put a focus on Friday, with the publication of a document, which will record an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrial nations facing the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final policy agreement on greenhouse gas control, has identified both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But he was seen as important progress in a negotiation that is about to take place, as next week more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, which was drawn up by a UN working group specifically set up for this purpose, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to the poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature increase that policy-makers would contribute to.
The process is given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, head of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has designed the six-page document, has put together a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, has called "the big whole."
It shows the basis of a possible agreement where the industrial nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25-45% by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15-30% over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95% by 2050.
The European Community has also given a boost to the talks on Friday through its commitment to provide US $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from the master of floods and droughts to the prevention of deforestation.
Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks in the last week.
The American climate expert Todd Stern has rejected formulations that require binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, if they are not financed by the industrialized countries.
This train announced that the Obama government is running a harder line with China than the Bush government's representative not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging economies standing up and taking action, says Stern, who also complained that the text does not go far enough, to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his opinion one hour after the Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the leading American climate negotiator was either missing "reason" or it was "highly irresponsible" of him that he said at the beginning of the week that the United States would not help China financially to master global warming.
As the future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake, both within the industrial nations and between the industrial nations and the emerging economies have opened up breaklines.
The current fight is also related to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to the rescue of the planet, where China and the United States command themselves for their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous measures.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the great powers are fighting for who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have gone more aggressive in taking the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions into account for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will develop a new economic dominance, says Ulate, who is also active as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding Treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will lead to a political agreement in the best case.
The alliance of the small island states with 43 members presented a 24-page draft Treaty on the early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who is leading the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states "is putting political pressure on the whole political process," partly because they are now united and are calling for action from emerging countries, such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency when delegates focused on the fact that most of the open questions had to be resolved before the leaders arrived to reach an agreement.
High-level representatives, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Vice-Minister, escaped their aircraft and rained through the Bella Center's course to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to cover claims that will be negotiated during the next week.
The pure extent of the meeting -- 13,000 people go into and out of the Congress Centre every day, guitar-playing activists take part in night shows, in which they make fun of the countries that they think are betraying and selling, and draft contracts are handed over by hand rather than by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all major ministers are here now and from Wednesday, 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice-President for Global Policy of the Organization Conservation International.
