The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other meat-eating dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-tall animal ran on two strong hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reported Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine of Thursday.
The animal lived around 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was in a dry zone of the Pangaea supercontinent at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of the dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists started digging at the Ghost Ranch in the North of New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaurs bones in one day, which is unprecedented for trias deposits, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as new species.
In the course of the excavation they brought together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Found confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" is from the Sun God of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an extraordinary finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare, most of the time one finds only single fragments."
Other dinosaurs experts do not necessarily share enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says about Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
After the current teaching opinion, the dinosaurs first showed up about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the allocation of these Ur-Dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the lizards split into their three main development lines: the meat-eating theropodes, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, which were known as the "long-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants-eating ornithischia (bird's pelvic saurus), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air sacks, as well as the descendants of the theopodes, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
In Tawa hallae the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge saurods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far lived in South America, the researchers follow that the lizards first showed up there.
As a result, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America across all the earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent of Pangäa.
The fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropodes, speaks of this.
The three cannot be derived from a common, emigrated ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are, of course, contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonner Paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be a distorted picture, because in South America there have been a very large number of primitive Dino fossils, while there is little to be found on other continents.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare side line of the reptile tribe to the dominant agricultural animals of the Earth's Middle Ages, it is still mysterious.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flight saurers and with many other lizards.
At the end of the Trias, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship at the border from the Trias to the Jura died.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass death that happened to survive the dinosaurs, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story didn't last forever.
150 million years later, a meteor attack by a group of animals helped to blossom, which had also developed in the Trias and since then has been a shadow life: the mammals.
