Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now compulsory
As in the case of the ABS anti-blocking braking system and as is happening now with the stability control ESP, the emergency braking systems need to become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and light small vehicles, and for the remaining vehicles a period of time has been set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the action adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many road accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake maneuver which the system recognizes on the brake pedal using the brake strength carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not get to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not fully stopped.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, is used with maximum force in the braking system and thus reduces the braking time and therefore the brake distance that a car provides during the braking process.
According to a study by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are affected could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
There would be even less accidents - it is expected that any fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time it already has a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant shall exercise the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to minimise the damage.
